		<item>
		<title>The Power of Shared Knowledge</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2012/11/the-power-of-shared-knowledge/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2012/11/the-power-of-shared-knowledge/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 06 Nov 2012 12:00:16 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[advice]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[alignment]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[personal development]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=756</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Growing up, arranged marriage was treated as a punchline. It was presented in movies and other popular culture as an outdated, senseless tradition that sought only to control the young and run contrary to American notions of freedom. To be &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/11/the-power-of-shared-knowledge/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/11/the-power-of-shared-knowledge/">The Power of Shared Knowledge</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Growing up, arranged marriage was treated as a punchline. It was presented in movies and other popular culture as an outdated, senseless tradition that sought only to control the young and run contrary to American notions of freedom.</p>
<p>To be clear: no, this article will not suggest that we go back to a world of arranged marriages. People exercising their own choice to select a life partner &#8211; or even IF they select a life partner &#8211; is the more humane approach. But it is folly to discount centuries-old traditions as ignorant and senseless; we have tossed out the proverbial baby with the bathwater. Indeed, in discarding arranged marriage we did away with the valuable knowledge and experience of elders.</p>
<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Power of Shared Knowledge" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Chairs.jpg" alt="Chairs" /><br />
<figcaption>Picking the people who will best complement you is often a matter of common sense.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>It is a statistical fact that people with particular similarities are more likely to have lasting, successful marriages. Similar cultural backgrounds. Similar socio-economic groups. Similar religious and spiritual grounding. Complementary personality traits. In trying to espouse American values of freedom our popular culture focused on romantic comedies with quirky, unexpected, and decidedly different boy-meets-girl stories. This cheeky brand of entertainment entirely ignored the fact that these relationships are statistically less likely to work. While, certainly, wonderful relationships come out of improbable pairings the reality is a competent old-world matchmaker would probably be more likely to give you a happy pairing. It would just be with a less exotic choice, someone more like you.</p>
<p>A lot of what we do with Facio flirts with seeming to tell people what they should do. It is not our intent. We can present data, insight, statistics, probabilities. But we can&#8217;t tell you one way or another what you should do. Those choices are yours; we just want them to be more informed. We want you to make the choices, but we want to &#8211; with our modern tools and frameworks &#8211; serve the same role the wise and experienced once served when the world was slower and smaller. This brand of shared knowledge, passed from the old to the young, has been devalued on our culture. It shouldn&#8217;t be and, to what degree we are able to contribute wisdom, we surely intend to do so.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/11/the-power-of-shared-knowledge/">The Power of Shared Knowledge</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://facio.com/blog/2012/11/the-power-of-shared-knowledge/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Living is growing</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2012/10/living-is-growing/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2012/10/living-is-growing/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 16 Oct 2012 09:00:34 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[personal development]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=685</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>We typically equate personal growth as a positive, proactive thing.In reality, each of us are growing constantly. Not all of that growth is healthy. It doesn&#8217;t always make our lives better. It is not always good for us. And it &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/10/living-is-growing/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/10/living-is-growing/">Living is growing</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>We typically equate personal growth as a positive, proactive thing.In reality, each of us are growing constantly. Not all of that growth is healthy. It doesn&#8217;t always make our lives better. It is not always good for us. And it is not always fast. But it is growth, of one kind or another.</p>
<p>I grew in very different ways during college years than many of my peers. I was already married, and by my third year had a child. My opportunities to grow socially were certainly limited and, because I was not challenged by school, I didn&#8217;t try and thus was not growing as I could have intellectually. On the other hand, I was growing in less traditional ways for a very young man: I was learning skills of patience, discipline and commitment. In my creative side projects, I was learning how to plan, manage and execute successful initiatives. Of course, while university was supposed to be my context for growth it actually provided very little. Most of my growth happened around my living in a nuclear family at a very young age. It is a path that few of my fellow college-bound peers shared. In retrospect my choices would have been different, but at least I am able to appreciate what I had.</p>
<p>We have been taught to think of growth as something specific and intentional. When you want to learn something, you take the right course or read the right book. When you want to get healthy, you follow a prescribed regiment of diet and/or exercise. When you want to improve emotionally you work with a coach or a therapist. Often these are the quickest or most efficient paths to a particular kind of growth, but they are only activated when we become aware of the choices we are making, identify some explicit context for improvement, and intentionally implement appropriate solutions.</p>
<p>There is a long tradition of making intentional choices and changes around our physical health. Diet and exercise represent enormous first world industries and are inextricably tied to our sense of self, and even self-worth. At the same time, few people bring a similar awareness to their behavioural and inter-personal selves. Yes, therapy is more mainstream and accepted than it has ever been, but more often it is a reactive effort to deal with trauma than a proactive effort to grow in the best possible way. In a business context executive coaches, and even life coaches, have a place. Many executives and rising managers have enjoyed the benefits of these engagements. But rather than companies seeing these as mission-critical investments they are the sort of thing that usually is indulged when the good times are rolling but among the first cuts when it is time to tighten our belts.</p>
<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Leadership And Context" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Awareness.jpg" alt="Albert Einstein" /></p>
<figcaption>Being intentional about our life and choices creates better outcomes.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>The choices we make each day define who we are, and who we will become. Awareness of calorie counts, fat and cholesterol have been part of our collective consciousness for over a century. Attention to how many steps we take each day, times we work out each week, and repetitions we can complete on a machine are more recent concerns largely tied to the sedentary work so many of us find ourselves in. However we still do not pay intentional, perpetual attention to our emotional and behavioural selves. We live, we reign in behaviours that are conspicuously aggressive or malignant, but for the most part we simply press forward being the person we appear to be, not striving to grow in different and more beneficial ways.</p>
<p>One of our goals with Facio is to help people live more intentionally. Everything people do is growth of one sort or another. Maybe for the better; maybe for the worse. Maybe fast and effective; maybe slow and suboptimal. The choices we make, the way we live each moment of each day, is growing us in ways we rarely have awareness of.</p>
<p>Awareness. That&#8217;s the first step. Being aware of how we behave and intersect with others surfaces opportunities to grow and mindfully work toward them. The result will be that we realize more of our best selves and almost certainly participate in more positive and productive ways with the people and organizations we care about. No matter what we will be growing in one way or another; we deserve to enjoy the benefits of growing well.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/10/living-is-growing/">Living is growing</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
